@startuml
title casbinjs/react - Usage Flow

skinparam shadowing false

actor ReactComponent as Component
participant "Consumer Fetch Layer" as FetchLayer
participant "External Endpoint" as Endpoint
box "casbinjs/react"
participant "AuthzProvider" as Provider
participant "useAuthz()" as UseAuthz
participant "usePermissionsEnforcer()" as UsePermissionsEnforcer
end box
box "casbinjs/core"
participant "Authorizer" as Authorizer
end box

== Initialization ==

FetchLayer -> Endpoint : fetch AuthorizationPayload
Endpoint --> FetchLayer : AuthorizationPayload
FetchLayer -> Authorizer : create / replace payload
FetchLayer -> Provider : render with authorizer\nor payload-derived state
Provider -> Authorizer : provide current authorizer via context

== Hook consumption ==

Component -> UseAuthz : useAuthz()
UseAuthz -> Provider : consume context
Provider --> UseAuthz : authorizer helpers
UseAuthz --> Component : can / canAny / canAll / getEnforcer

Component -> UsePermissionsEnforcer : usePermissionsEnforcer()
UsePermissionsEnforcer -> UseAuthz : compose base authz hook
UseAuthz --> UsePermissionsEnforcer : can(...)
UsePermissionsEnforcer --> Component : canView / canUpdate / canDelete / etc.

== Permission checks ==

Component -> UseAuthz : can(action, resourceType, resourceId)
UseAuthz -> Authorizer : can(action, resourceKey)
Authorizer --> UseAuthz : boolean
UseAuthz --> Component : boolean

note over FetchLayer,Endpoint
Fetching stays app-owned.
tRPC is one possible consumer choice,
not part of the library contract.
end note

note over Provider,UsePermissionsEnforcer
casbinjs/react is the ready-to-use React layer.
end note

note over Authorizer
casbinjs/core remains the vanilla-ready interface.
end note
@enduml
